# we can use following code to remove the features that have correlation over 0.6
# Create correlation matrix
corr_matrix = AAA.corr().abs()

# Select upper triangle of correlation matrix
upper = corr_matrix.where(np.triu(np.ones(corr_matrix.shape), k=1).astype(np.bool))

# Find index of feature columns with correlation greater than 0.60
to_drop = [column for column in upper.columns if any(upper[column] > 0.6)]

AAA_new1 = AAA.drop(to_drop, axis=1)

Categorizing the target variable¶

In [575]:
# Convert the target variable into categories for classification class
AAA_new2 = AAA_new1
def Absenteeism_hours_to_categories(x):
    if x == 0:
        return 0
    if 0 < x <= 8:
        return 1
    if 8 < x <= 40:
        return 2
    if x > 40:
        return 3
AAA_new2['Absenteeism_Class'] = AAA_new2['Absenteeism time in hours'].apply(Absenteeism_hours_to_categories)
AAA_new2['Absenteeism_Class'] = AAA_new2['Absenteeism_Class'].astype(int)
AAA_new1 = AAA_new1.drop(['Absenteeism_Class'],axis=1)
AAA_new = AAA_new2.drop(['Absenteeism time in hours'],axis=1)

# First, lets try k-means clustering
# Code to generate elbow graph to find the best value for number of cluters, k
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans 

sse = {} 
last_sse = 17592402.70373319 
for k in range(2, 15): 
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=1234).fit(AAA_C) 
    AAA_C["clusters"] = kmeans.labels_ 
    #print(data["clusters"]) 
    sse[k] = kmeans.inertia_ 
    # Inertia: Sum of distances of samples to their closest cluster center 
    change_per = (last_sse-kmeans.inertia_)/last_sse*100 
    print ('At k= ',k,'The percentage of change in SSE is ',change_per,'%')
    last_sse = kmeans.inertia_ 
plt.figure() 
plt.plot(list(sse.keys()), list(sse.values())) 
plt.xlabel("Number of cluster") 
plt.ylabel("SSE") 
plt.show()

# Design a K means algorithm
# Design a model with best k=4
X = AAA_C.drop(['Absenteeism_Class'],axis=1)
y = AAA_C['Absenteeism_Class']

scaler = StandardScaler()
# scaler = MinMaxScaler()
scaler.fit(X)
X_scaled = scaler.transform(X)
# The MinMaxScaler shifts the data such that all features are exactly between 0 and 1
# The StandardScaler in scikit-learn ensures that for each feature the mean is 0 and variance is 1, bringing all features to the same magnitude
# However, this scaling does not ensure any particular minimum or maximum values for the features.

kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=4, random_state=1234).fit(X_scaled)

The DBSCAN Clustering does give better result than k-means clustering (not on accuracy but on ground truth ARI)¶

The clustering results for both k-means & DBSCAN are not great. This is because the standard k-means & DBSCAN clustering algorithm isn't directly applicable to categorical data, and lot of features in our data are categorial. The sample space for categorical data is discrete, and doesn't have a natural origin. A Euclidean distance function on such a space isn't really meaningful. The other reason is we categorized our absenteeism class based on only the Absenteeism time in hours, but k-means & DBSCAN is clustering the records on the basis of the other features also, as a result there is a lot of misclassification.¶

# To apply the supervised classification on the scaled data, we also need to transform the test data.
# This is again done by calling the transform method, this time on X_test

X_test_scaled = scaler.transform(X_test)
# print test data properties after scaling
print("per-feature minimum after scaling:\n{}".format(X_test_scaled.min(axis=0)))
print("per-feature maximum after scaling:\n{}".format(X_test_scaled.max(axis=0)))

# Maybe somewhat surprisingly, you can see that for the test set, after scaling, the min and max are not 0 and 1
# Some of the features are even outside the 0-1 range!
# The exaplnation is that the MinMaxScaler (and all the other scalers) always applies exactly the same transformation to the training and test set.
# This means the transform method always subtracts the training set minimum and divides by the training set range,
# which might be different from the minimum and range for the test set

Although the decision tree (and its ensemble models) does give good results with proper pruning but, as expected, they do suffer from overfitting. Another concern with decision tree model is that one of our class (Class 0 = No Absence) dominate the other classes, hence the model is likely to be biased. So, we can use decision tree models (or atleast refer its accuracy to the other models) because they are robust to preprocessing and data, and hence can be used as such without much paramter tuning.¶

Naive Bayes Classifier and KNN does not give us a good accuracy result, because there was no prori probability for Naive Bayes to refer to that can improve its accuracy while KNN always does badly on sparse data, and in our data some of the features had lots of values as zeros.¶

So to conclude, the Logistic Regression Classifier (with C=100 and L1 regularization parameter) gives us the best result, whereas the other classifiers struggled with either overfitting or underfitting.¶
